<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-04-20T11:23:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-04-20T11:23:00-05:00" n="138" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d138">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">812.00/23661: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at Nogales</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Dyer</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Nogales, Ariz.</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-04-20T09:00:00-07:23"><hi rend="italic">April 20, 1920—9
                                    a.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 1:48 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>Governor wired me last night that he has ordered 50 soldiers to
                                Cananea. General Serrano here yesterday said States of Michoacán,
                                    <pb facs="0242" n="142" xml:id="pg_142"/> Hidalgo, Guerrero,
                                Colima, Jalisco, Zacatecas and Tabasco are openly favoring Sonora
                                attitude.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Dyer</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>